{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17361"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17361"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10051"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75077"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10051"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7814"},{"type":"tags","id":"7817"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23535"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75077"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is analysing responses from a 20-item questionnaire measuring psychological well-being. The questionnaire includes questions about mood, energy levels, sleep quality, appetite, and social interactions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary purpose of using factor analysis for this questionnaire?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["To identify underlying constructs that explain patterns of correlation between items","To predict future psychological outcomes from questionnaire responses","To compare mean scores between different participant groups","To establish cut-off scores for clinical diagnosis","To determine the reliability of individual questionnaire items"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFactor analysis is a multivariate statistical technique that reduces a large number of variables into a smaller set of underlying dimensions or factors. It examines the correlations between variables to identify groups of items that vary together, suggesting they measure the same underlying construct. The technique can be either exploratory (to discover the underlying structure) or confirmatory (to test a hypothesised structure).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdentifying underlying constructs that explain patterns of correlation between items\u003C/strong\u003E is therefore the primary purpose of factor analysis. This statistical method helps researchers understand the latent structure of the questionnaire by revealing which items cluster together, suggesting they measure similar underlying concepts or factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetermining the reliability of individual questionnaire items\u003C/strong\u003E - This would typically involve calculating Cronbach\u0027s alpha or test-retest reliability, not factor analysis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComparing mean scores between different participant groups\u003C/strong\u003E - This would require different statistical tests like t-tests or ANOVA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPredicting future psychological outcomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This would require predictive modelling techniques like regression analysis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEstablishing cut-off scores for clinical diagnosis\u003C/strong\u003E - This would involve sensitivity/specificity analysis or ROC curves\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFactor analysis might reveal that the 20 items actually measure three or four underlying factors (e.g., mood/affect, physical symptoms, social functioning). This helps in understanding the questionnaire\u0027s structure and potentially reducing the number of items while maintaining its measurement properties.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Factor analysis is a statistical method that identifies underlying constructs (factors) that explain patterns of correlations among observed variables.","Principal components analysis is a specific type of factor analysis that creates uncorrelated linear combinations of variables to explain maximum variance.","Factor loadings indicate the strength and direction of correlation between variables and their underlying factors."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T21:17:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-28T21:19:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10051"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75077"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":